      "writtenOn": "2020-04-02T16:37:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i might be missing something, but why are we mirroring protos here? \nif that\u0027s how starlark-for-configs should be written then starlark adds a significant amount of overhead here.\n\ncan\u0027t we use the protos?\n\n+Vadim",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 61,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "7e443db75d6cccf1e8101e1f0a1d3b46ad2b0383",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "11662750_c23b9ad6",
        "filename": "lucicfg/starlark/stdlib/internal/luci/lib/resultdb.star",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 61,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-03T22:06:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Using protos as opaque return values of e.g. resultdb.settings(...) is OK. Asking users to use load(\"@...\") and construct protos by hand as public API is not OK. lucicfg provides an API layer higher than raw protos. Raw protos should not stick out from lucicfg public API.\n\nThe value of constructors like resultdb.settings(...) is more tight type validation that happens at the moment the message is constructed.\n\nAnother minor advantage is that structs are frozen (and protos are not). But it\u0027s not crucial.",
      "parentUuid": "08be3f40_593f18f2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 61,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "7e443db75d6cccf1e8101e1f0a1d3b46ad2b0383",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "484ffb56_ed2cc7b7",
        "filename": "lucicfg/starlark/stdlib/internal/luci/lib/resultdb.star",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 61,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-03T22:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "all of this sgtm. \n\nI am worried about the maintenance cost here. Next time we add a field to this proto, we need to update the starlark layer again. Updating the starlark portion is unavoidable, but can be *minimized*.\n\nI see the value in functions. I see less value in structs. They add a layer of indirection that does *NOT* provide a new level of abstraction (because they mirror proto fields 1:1, at least in this case). This means they add work for us, without adding a lot of value. This makes me think that these functions should return protos (or return node that contain protos). Then the change in generators.go would be minimial because it wouldn\u0027t have to convert structs-to-protos. WDYT?\n\nCan a node property be a proto? If a node must be immutable, can we serialize the proto when putting it in the node, and then deserialize it back later? is there a more efficient way of doing this, maybe by adding support at the go level?",
      "parentUuid": "11662750_c23b9ad6",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 61,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "7e443db75d6cccf1e8101e1f0a1d3b46ad2b0383",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d69127c2_1f316a09",
        "filename": "lucicfg/starlark/stdlib/internal/luci/lib/resultdb.star",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 61,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-03T23:00:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Note properties can be protos and they will be frozen automatically when they are added to nodes. I was meaning slightly different thing. With structs the following is not possible.\n\ns \u003d resultdb.settings(enabled \u003d False)\ns.enabled \u003d True\n\nWith protos it will be possible.\n\nIt\u0027s not a big deal.",
      "parentUuid": "484ffb56_ed2cc7b7",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 61,
        "endChar": 0
      },
      "revId": "7e443db75d6cccf1e8101e1f0a1d3b46ad2b0383",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
